---
import Layout from '../layouts/BlogPost.astro';
---

<Layout
	title="About dataGriff"
	description="A forty-something working developer from the South Wales valleys. Honest walkthroughs, strong opinions, source-controlled everything."
	date={new Date('2021-08-08')}
>
	<img src="/assets/datagriff.png" alt="dataGriff portrait" class="portrait" width="200" height="200" />

	<p>
		I'm dataGriff, a forty-something working developer from the South Wales valleys. I've spent my
		career in data engineering, DevOps, and anything involving making systems smaller, cheaper, and
		more yours. These days that includes working with AI agents alongside everything else. The blog
		is called hungovercoders because that's more honest than whatever I'd have come up with sober.
	</p>

	<p>
		The posts are walkthroughs of things I actually built. Not theoretical, not sanitised. Some
		written on a Friday night, most polished on a Sunday morning with the dog asleep on the sofa.
		The code ran on my laptop first and I'll tell you when it didn't go to plan, because that's the
		bit the vendor docs leave out, and it's usually the most useful part.
	</p>

	<p>
		Alongside the writing I build apps and tools. See <a href="/projects">Projects</a> for the
		current set, live and in progress.
	</p>

	<p>
		AI is on the team now too. I work with Claude Code (and friends) daily: the agents scaffold,
		draft, refactor, type out the YAML I can't be bothered to. I do the judgement calls. When AI
		helped, I say so. That's more interesting than pretending I wrote every keystroke.
	</p>

	<h2>The worldview</h2>

	<p>Every post is quietly making one of these arguments:</p>

	<ul>
		<li><strong>Small, cheap, and yours beats big, fancy, and rented.</strong> Single binaries over JVM clusters. Static sites over CMS-as-a-service. Source-controlled config over click-ops.</li>
		<li><strong>If one slightly hungover person can't deploy it on a Tuesday, or a Saturday with a head on them, it's too complicated.</strong> Operational simplicity is a feature, not a constraint.</li>
		<li><strong>Source control everything that has behaviour.</strong> Configs, infrastructure, dashboards, prompts, especially prompts now. If it's not in git, it doesn't exist.</li>
		<li><strong>Shift left until it hurts, then shift left some more.</strong> Tests, linting, security, observability at the developer's keyboard, not in a separate pipeline three weeks downstream.</li>
		<li><strong>AI is a power tool, not a magic wand.</strong> Use it for the boring bits: scaffolding, refactoring, the YAML you can't be bothered to type. Stay opinionated about the rest. The model does the typing; you do the judgement.</li>
		<li><strong>Boring tech that works beats exciting tech that nearly works.</strong> Be enthusiastic about tools but suspicious of hype.</li>
	</ul>

	<p>
		I've been doing this long enough to have opinions, and long enough to have been wrong about half
		of them. The "what I'd do differently" section in every post is the honest bit.
	</p>

	<h2>Where to find me</h2>

	<ul>
		<li><a href="https://github.com/dataGriff">GitHub — dataGriff</a></li>
		<li><a href="https://youtube.com/@hungovercoders">YouTube — @hungovercoders</a></li>
		<li><a href="https://github.com/hungovercoders">GitHub org — hungovercoders</a></li>
	</ul>

	<p>Well done for reading this far, fellow hungovercoder. Cheers.</p>
</Layout>

